ABSTRACT Nonomuraea  rhodomycinica  NR4-ASC07T  is  a  rare  actinomycete  isolated from soil in Sirindhorn peat swamp forest. The crude extract  of  its  culture  broth  exhibited  antimicrobial  and  anticancer  against  diverse human pathogens and cancer cells. The chemical investigation  of the crude extract led to the isolation of two new metabolites named  nonomuric  acid  (1)  and  3-hydroxy  deoxydaunorubicinol  aglycone  (2), along with two known bioactive compounds [ε-rhodomycinone  (3)  and  7-deoxy-13-dihydrocarminomycinone  (4)].  Compounds  1  and 3 showed antimalarial activity with the half maximal inhibitory  concentration (IC50) of 8.00 and 8.88 μg mL−1, respectively. Compound  4 inhibited growth of Mycobacterium tuberculosis and Bacillus cereus  at the minimum inhibitory concentrations of 50.0 and 12.50 μg mL−1,  respectively. Every compound exhibited cytotoxicity against cancer  cells tested at IC50 ≥ 6.34 μg mL−1. These finding are the first report  of bioactive metabolites produced by strain NR4-ASC07T, suggesting  that  rare  actinomycetes  are  yet  promising  sources  for  novel  drug  discovery. ARTICLE HISTORY received 8 december 2017  accepted 7 February 2018 KEYWORDS rare actinomycetes;  Nonomuraea; Bioactive  compound; Nonomuric  acid; 3-hydroxy  deoxydaunorubicinol  aglycone

The genus Nonomuraea is a member of the family Streptosporangiaceae (Zhang et al. 1998).  Hitherto, the genus Nonomuraea comprises 43 species and a subspecies, while Nonomuraea  pusilla IFO14684T is the type species. Most species of the genus Nonomuraea have their  ecological niches in soil and sediment (Sungthong and Nakaew 2015; Sripreechasak et al.  2017). Flatt et al. 2013 revealed that Nonomureae spp. possess the polyketide synthase (PKS)  and non-ribosomal peptide genes that involve the biosynthetic pathways of various sec- ondary metabolites. A set of bioactive compounds produced by the genus Nonomureae was  reviewed by Sungthong and Nakaew (2015). For examples, the antimicrobial actinotiocin  from  N.  pusilla  IFO  14684T  (Tamura  et  al.  1973),  the  anthelmintic  macrolactams  from  Nonomuraea turkmeniaca MA7364 (Ayers et al. 2007), and brartemicin, the murine colon  carcinoma  26-L5  cell  inhibitor,  from  the  endophytic  Nonomuraea  sp. TP-A0870  (Igarashi   et  al.  2009).  A  recent  discovery  was  hypogeamicin  A,  an  anticancer  agent,  produced  by  Nonomuraea specus (Derewacz et al. 2014).

Nonomuraea rhodomycinica NR4-ASC07T was proposed recently as a novel species of the  genus Nonomureae; it was isolated from soil collected at Sirindhorn peat swamp forest in  Southern Thailand (Sripreechasak et al. 2017). Interestingly, strain NR4-ASC07T showed anti- microbial and anticancer against a set of human pathogens and cancer cells. In this study,  we aim at elucidating the bioactive metabolites produced by strain NR4-ASC07T by using  column chromatography (including Sephadex LH-20 column and HPLC) for purification, and  nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) technique and mass spectral analysis for structure deter- mination. The elucidated compounds were assayed for their bioactivities against a set of  test organisms (i.e. multidrug-resistant Plasmodium falciparum K-1, Mycobacterium tubercu- losis H37Ra, and Bacillus cereus) and cancer cells [i.e. oral human epidermoid carcinoma (KB),  human breast cancer (MCF-7), and human small cell lung cancer (NCI-H187)]. 2.  Results and discussion

Compound 1 was obtained in the form of white solid and revealed the molecular formula  of C19H26O5 by showing a sodium adduct mass ion peak at m/z 357.1679 in HRESIMS spec- trum. The 13C NMR spectrum (Figure S1) showed nineteen signals, which differentiated by  DEPT-135 spectrum, consisting of 2 methyl, 7 methylene, 4 methine, and 6 quaternary car- bons. The  IR  spectrum  displayed  a  broad  hydroxyl  absorption  at  3500–3000 cm−1  and  a  carbonyl absorption of carboxylic at 1711 cm−1. The COSY spectrum displayed 3 spin systems,  which included H2-1/H2-2/H-9b, H2-4/H2-5/H-5a, and H2-14/H-7/H2-8/H-9. In addition, the  HMBC spectrum showed correlations from H3-10 to C-3, C-3a, C-4, and C-9b; from H2-2 to  C-3; from H2-1 to C-2, C-3, C-9a, and C-9b; from H2-4 to C-5 and C-10; from H3-11 to C-5a, C-6,  C-7, and C-12; from H-5a to C-9; from H-9 to C-5a, C-7, C-8, and C-9b; from H2-12 to C-5a, C-6,  C-7, C-11, and C-13; from H2-14 to C-6, C-7, C-8, and C-15; and from H-9b to C-9a and C-2.  The NOESY spectrum showed cross-peak correlations from H-5a to H-7 and H-9b; from H3-10  to Hβ-4 and Hβ-5; and from H3-11 to Hβ-5. The spectroscopic evidence confirmed the chemical  structure with the relative configuration as shown in Figure 1 and nonomuric acid was given  as its trivial name.

Compound 2 was obtained in the form of dark red solid. The 1H NMR spectrum (Figure  S11) was similar to ε-rhodomycinone (3) (Essery and Doyle 1979), except the presence of an  Figure 1. chemical structures of compounds 1–4 isolated from Nonomuraea rhodomycinica Nr4-asc07t. additional methoxy signal at δH 3.84 and the absence of a triplet aromatic methine. The  HRESIMS spectrum confirmed the molecular formula C23H22O10 by showing the mass ion  peak at m/z 457.1137 [M − H]−. The 1H NMR spectrum indicated tetrasubstituted benzene  ring. In addition, the HMBC spectrum showed correlations from H-1 (δH 8.00) to C-3 (δC 157.9),  C-4a (δC 126.2), and C-12 (δC 185.5); from H-2 (δH 7.37) to C-4 (148.5) and C-12a (δC 124.9);  and from 4-OCH3 (δH 3.84) to C-4. The absence of a chelated hydroxyl proton also indicated  the replacement of the methoxy group at C-4. The similar optical rotation and CD spectrum  [Δε (nm):+6.74 (239 nm), −3.71 (296 nm),+1.71 (350 nm); Fig. S18] elaborated the same rel- ative configurations at C-7, C-9, and C-10 as those in compound 3. The chemical structure  of  compound  2  is  shown  in  Figure  1  with  a  name  3-hydroxy  deoxydaunorubicinol  aglycone.

The  NMR  information  of  the  known  compounds  including  ε-rhodomycinone  (3),  and  7-deoxy-13-dihydrocarminomycinone (4) (Figure 1) were agreed with those reported in the  literature (Ashcroft and Sutherland 1981; Johdo et al. 1991). In addition, the complete spectral  data (1H and 13C NMR data) of compounds 1, 2, and 4 are provided in Supporting Information  (Table S1) and physico-chemical properties of all compounds are given herein. Compounds 1 and 3 showed antagonistic activity against P. falciparum with IC50 8.00 and  8.88 μg mL−1,  respectively.  Compound  1  had  cytotoxicity  against  Vero  cells  at  IC50  12.50 μg mL−1, but compound 3 was inactive. Compounds 1–3 showed anticancer activity  against NCI-H187 with IC50 in a range of 6.34–45.88 μg mL−1 (Table S2). Only compound 4  revealed antibacterial activity against B. cereus and M. tuberculosis with MIC values of 12.5  and 50.0 μg mL−1, respectively, and exhibited low cytotoxicity against both cancerous and  non-cancerous cells in a range of 17.33 − >50 μg mL−1 (Table S2). The substituents of com- pounds 2 and 3 at C-3 and C-4 had beneficial effect on antimalarial and anticancer activities.  Compound 3 was earlier isolated from various Streptomyces spp. such as Streptomyces pur- purasceus (Brockmann and Franck 1955; Brockmann and Brockmann 1961), Streptomyces  griseoruber 4620 (Podojil et al. 1980), and Streptomyces sp. HPL Y-11472 (Reddy et al. 1985).  NATURAL PRODUCT RESEARCH

Compound 4 was formerly isolated from Actinomadura reseoviolacea (Nakagawa et al. 1983).  Both known compounds have not been reported for bioactivity but other related anthracy- clines  such  as  epelmycins  A-E  (ε-rhodomycinone  glycosides)  had  antimicrobial  activity  against both Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria (Johdo et al. 1991). Moreover, anth- racycline antibiotics such as doxorubicin, daunorubicin, and aclarubicin have also been used  as cancer therapeutic agents. 3.1.  General experimental procedures Column chromatography was performed on Sephadex LH-20 column using 100% MeOH as  eluent. HPLC was performed on a Dionex-Ultimate 3000 series equipped with a binary pump,  an autosampler, and diode array detector. Semi-preparative HPLC was performed on a Sunfire  C18 column from Waters (particle size 5 μm, diam. 19 × 150 mm2). Preparative HPLC was  performed on a Sunfire C18 column from Waters (particle size 10 μm, diam. 19 × 250 mm2).  FT-IR spectra were measured on a Bruker ALPHA spectrometer. UV spectra were performed  in MeOH on a Spekol 1200 spectrophotometer from Analytik Jena. Optical rotations were  measured on a JASCO P-1030 digital polarimeter. NMR spectra were recorded either on a  Bruker Avance 500 MHz NMR spectrometer or a Bruker Avance III 400 MHz NMR spectrometer  using DMSO-d6 (δH 2.50, δC 39.49) as an internal standard. HRESIMS data were obtained from  a Bruker MicrOTOF spectrometer. All compounds used as positive controls for bioactivity  screening were bought from Sigma-Aldrich. The software ChemDrawTM Ultra 12.0 was used  to draw all chemical structures. 3.2.  Biological material

N. rhodomycinica NR4-ASC07T was isolated from a soil sample collected at Sirindhorn peat  swamp forest, Narathiwat province, Thailand (Sripreechasak et al. 2017) and deposited at  Thailand Bioresource Research Center (TBRC) with the registration number TBRC6557. 3.3.  Fermentation, extraction and isolation Strain NR4-ASC07T was grown on ISP2 agar medium pH 7.2, containing 4 g yeast extract,  10 g malt extract, 4 g dextrose, 20 g agar powder in 1L of distilled water at 30 °C for 4 days.  The stock culture was inoculated into 20 × 250 mL Erlenmeyer flasks, which each contained  150 mL of International Streptomyces Project medium 2 (ISP2). The culture broth was incu- bated on a rotary shaker (200 rpm) at 30 °C for 4 days. Then, the culture broth (20 flasks) was  transferred into 80 × 1 L Erlenmeyer flasks, which each contained 250 mL of wheat germ- starch production medium pH 7.3, containing 20 g soluble starch, 5 g glycerol, 10 g defatted  wheat germ, 3 g meat extract, 3 g yeast extract and 3 g CaCO3 in 1 L of distilled water. The  wheat germ-starch production medium (80 flasks) was cultivated for 14 days at 30 °C on  rotary shakers (200 rpm). After 14 days of incubation, the whole culture broth was extracted  three times using an equal volume of EtOAc, and the extract was dried over Na2SO4. The  EtOAc residue was evaporated till dry, which yield a brown gum extract of 3 g. The extract  was fractionated through a Sephadex LH-20 column to give two fractions.

The first fraction (1.3 g) was separated by a Sephadex LH-20 column to give two subfrac- tions (F1F1 and F1F2). Subfraction F1F1 was purified by a preparative HPLC, eluted with a  linear gradient system of 15–70% CH3CN in H2O over 30 min at the flow rate of 15 mL min−1,  to furnish compound 1 (23.4 mg). Subfraction F1F2 (93 mg) was purified by a preparative  HPLC, eluted with a linear gradient system of 10–70% CH3CN in H2O over 30 min at the flow  rate of 15 mL min−1, to give compound 1 (9.2 mg). The second fraction (1.3 g) was passed through a Sephadex LH-20 column to give 2 subfrac- tions (F2F1 and F2F2). Subfraction F2F1 (0.2 g) was purified by a preparative HPLC, eluted with  a linear gradient system of 10–65% CH3CN in H2O over 30 min at the flow rate of 15 mL min−1,  to give compound 3 (10.6 mg). Subfraction F2F2 (0.3 g) was subsequently fractioned by a pre- parative HPLC, eluted with a linear gradient system of 10–65% CH3CN in H2O over 30 min at  the flow rate of 15 mL min−1, to give compounds 2 (7.0 mg), 4 (3.0 mg) and 3 (71.3 mg).

Antibacterial  activity  against  B.  cereus  ATCC  11778  and  cytotoxicity  test  against  KB  (oral  human epidermoid carcinoma, ATCC CCL-17), MCF-7 (human breast cancer, ATCC HTB-22),  and  NCI-H187  (human  small  cell  lung  cancer,  ATCC  CRL-5804)  cell  lines  were  tested  by  resazurin microplate assay (O’Brien et al. 2000; Sarker et al. 2007). Vancomycin was used as  a positive control for antibacterial assay. Ellipticine and doxorubicin were used as the positive  controls for anti-KB and anti-NCI-H187 tests, while tamoxifen and doxorubicin served as the  NATURAL PRODUCT RESEARCH

positive  controls  for  anti-MCF-7  test.  The  green  fluorescent  protein  microplate  assay  (Changsen  et  al.  2003)  was  used  for  the  cytotoxicity  test  against  a  normal  cell  line, Vero   cell  (African  green  monkey  kidney  fibroblasts,  ATCC  CCL-81)  and  antibacterial  against   M. tuberculosis H37Ra (ATCC 25177). Ellipticine served as the positive control for cytotoxicity  test against Vero cell, while isoniazid, ofloxacin, rifampicin, and ethambutol were used as  the positive controls for anti-M. tuberculosis activity. Antimalarial assay against P. falciparum  (K-1, multi-drug resistant strain) was performed by using the microculture radioisotope tech- nique (Desjardins et al. 1979), and dihydroartemisinin and mefloquine served as the positive  controls. The 0.5% (v/v) dimethylsulfoxide (DMSO) was used as the negative control for most  assays, except for the antimalarial test that used at 0.1% (v/v) DMSO. The IC50 represents the  concentration that reduced the cell growth by 50% and the minimum inhibitory concentra- tion (MIC) represents the lowest concentration that inhibited 90% of bacterial growth.

Four compounds including nonomuric acid (1), 3-hydroxy deoxydaunorubicinol aglycone  (2), ε-rhodomycinone (3), and 7-deoxy-13-dihydrocarminomycinone (4) have been isolated  from the rare actinomycete, N. rhodomycinica NR4-ASC07T. Compounds 1 and 3 showed  antimalarial activity at IC50 values of 8.00 and 8.88 μg mL−1, respectively. Compound 4 inhib- ited growth of M. tuberculosis and B. cereus at MIC of 50.0 and 12.50 mL min−1, respectively.  Compound 1 possessed cytotoxicity against Vero cell with IC50 value of 12.50 mL min−1, while  compound 3 exhibited anticancer activity against NCI-H187 with IC50 value of 6.34 mL min−1.
